===Etymology===
(1386) {{etyl|enm}} ''[[armee#Middle English|armee]]'' from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|armee||lang=fro}} (French {{term|armée|lang=fr}}), from Proto-Romance ''[[armata]]'', from M.L. armata "armed force", a noun taken from the past participle of {{etyl|la}} {{term|armare||lang=la|to [[arm]]}}, itself related to ''[[arma]]'' "tools, arms", from {{proto|Indo-European|ar-|to fit together|lang=}}. Displaced native {{enm}} ''[[here#Middle English|here, heare]]'' "army" (from {{ang}} ''[[here#Old English|here]]'' "army"), {{enm}} ''[[ferde#Middle English|ferde]]'' "army, militia" (from {{ang}} ''[[fyrd#Old English|fierd, fyrd]]'' "national army, militia"), {{enm}} ''[[trume#Middle English|trume, trome]]'' "army, troop" (from {{ang}} ''[[truma#Old English|truma]]'' "legion, company, troop"), {{enm}} ''[[wored#Middle English|wored]]'' "army" (from {{ang}} ''[[werod#Old English|werod, weorod]]'' "company, host, band, army"), {{ang}} ''[[gefylce#Old English|ġefylce]]'' "army, host".

